Creating an Aminet Hierarchy
****************************

This chapter explains how to create your first local Aminet mirror.
Please make sure that MirrorManager is installed and configured before
you go on reading here.  See @{"Installation" Link "Installation"}, @{"Configuring" Link "Configuring"} for details.

The first thing you need is an Aminet @{b}TREE@{ub} file.  This file is
available (e.g. via @{b}ftp@{ub}) from any Aminet site in @{b}info/adt/tree@{ub}.  You
can of course also use the @{b}ALs@{ub} tool to create such a file from an
existing Aminet mirror.  See @{"ALs" Link "ALs"}, for details.

To be written...


@EndNode

@Node "Using the ListView" "MirrorManager.guide/Using the ListView"
@Next "Menu Items"
@Prev "Creating a Mirror"
@Toc "Main"

Description of the Listview Items
*********************************

When starting MirrorManager with the configuration script
@{b}MirrorManager.rexx@{ub} last will add some items to the listview.  This
chapter will explain the use of these items.

You must have configured the file @{b}MirrorManager.rexx@{ub} to follow the
steps below.  See @{"Configuring" Link "Configuring"}, for more information.  You might want to
skip this chapter if you don't want to use the MUI application.

@{b}Create/Update Aminet TREE@{ub}
     This item executes @{b}MakeTree@{ub} in order to create the complete Aminet
     directory hierarchy from your Aminet @{b}TREE@{ub} file.  A filenote will
     be added to all directories listed in the @{b}TREE@{ub} file.

@{b}Delete Empty Directories@{ub}
     This item executes @{b}CutTree.mm@{ub} on your Aminet directory which will
     delete all empty directories there.

@{b}Update Aminet DirNotes@{ub}
     For each existing directory in your Aminet Hierarchy, a filenote
     will be added.  The filenote will be read from the Aminet @{b}TREE@{ub}
     file.

@{b}Add FileNotes to INCOMING@{ub}
     For all files in your incoming directory a filenote will be added.
     Last will be looked up in the Aminet @{b}INDEX@{ub} file.

@{b}Add FileNotes from RECENT@{ub}
     Works like @{b}Add FileNotes to INCOMING@{ub} except that the filenotes
     will be looked up in the @{b}RECENT@{ub} file.

@{b}Add FileNotes from WANTED@{ub}
     Works like @{b}Add FileNotes to INCOMING@{ub} except that the filenotes
     will be looked up in the @{b}WANTED@{ub} file.

@{b}Cleanup INCOMING@{ub}
     Works like @{b}Add FileNotes to INCOMING@{ub}.  Additionally the files will
     be moved into the correct directory in your Aminet hierarchy.
     Non-existant directories will be created.

@{b}Cleanup with new RECENT@{ub}
     Works like @{b}Cleanup INCOMING@{ub} except that the filenotes and the
     destination directory will be looked up in the @{b}RECENT@{ub} file.

@{b}Create FAST Index@{ub}
     Splits the Aminet @{b}INDEX@{ub} file and creates several small @{b}FAST@{ub} index
     files.  These files will be written to the fast index path which
     has been asked for in the @{b}Configure@{ub} script.

@{b}Create/Update LOCAL Index@{ub}
     A local index file will be created for your local Aminet mirror.

@{b}Edit LOCAL Index File@{ub}
     Edits your local Aminet mirror's index file.

@{b}Reorganize Local Mirror@{ub}
     Compares the contents of your local index file with the Aminet
     @{b}INDEX@{ub} file.  Files located in a different directory than listed in
     the Aminet @{b}INDEX@{ub} file will me moved to the correct location.
     Non-existant directories will be created automatically.

     Files which do not exist in the Aminet @{b}INDEX@{ub} will be moved to the
     @{b}KickedPath@{ub}, a directory which has been asked for in the @{b}Configure@{ub}
     script.

@{b}Re-Insert Kicked Out Files@{ub}
     Files which have been moved to the @{b}KickedPath@{ub} (e.g. by @{b}Reorganize
     Local Mirror@{ub}) will be moved back to their former location.

          @{i}Caution:@{ui} This operation needs your former local index file to
          look up the kicked out files' locations.  I.e. you should not
          update your local index file after calling @{b}Reorganize Local Mirror@{ub}
          if you want to move back some of the kicked out files into
          their old directories.

@{b}Sort Aminet INDEX File@{ub}
     Some people prefer an Aminet @{b}INDEX@{ub} file which is sorted by
     filenames, not by directories.  This item asks you for the first
     sorting creterium and then sorts the Aminet @{b}INDEX@{ub} file accordingly.

@{b}Edit Aminet INDEX File@{ub}
     This item runs an Editor and loads the Aminet @{b}INDEX@{ub} file.

@{b}Edit WANTED Index@{ub}
     This item runs an Editor and loads your @{b}WANTED@{ub} file.

@{b}Edit Configuration Script@{ub}
     This item runs an Editor and loads this configuration sctiptfile.


@EndNode

@Node "Menu Items" "MirrorManager.guide/Menu Items"
@Next "ARexx Scripts"
@Prev "Using the ListView"
@Toc "Main"

Menu Items and Menu Structure
*****************************

The @{b}Project@{ub} Menu
================

@{b}Load...@{ub}
     This will bring up a filerequester asking for a MirrorManager
     configuration.

     Because MirrorManager configurations are based on ARexx it will be
     loaded by executing it as an ARexx script.  I.e. these @{b}.mm@{ub} scripts
     configure MirrorManager via its ARexx port.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}LOAD@{ub}

@{b}Save@{ub}
     This will write your current configuration to disk without asking
     for a filename. It will be written over the last loaded
     configuration which will be deleted by this action. So be careful
     with this command!

     See also: ARexx command @{b}SAVE@{ub}

@{b}Save As...@{ub}
     This will bring up a filerequester asking for a name under which
     you would like to save your current configuration.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}SAVE@{ub}

@{b}Locked@{ub}
     This switch is set by MirrorManager whenever it executes an ARexx
     script or command and is unset as soon as MirrorManager has
     finished processing and is idle again.

     If you unset this switch you are able to execute further ARexx
     commands but this might be dangerous:
        - Most ARexx scripts in the MirrorManager package work directly
          on your files, moving them from one directory to another,
          adding filenotes etc.

        - Every MirrorManager ARexx script writes information into the
          MirrorManager Working Window.

     Because of these two facts the scripts might `disturb' each other.
     So the default behaviour of the scripts is to lock the
     MirrorManager GUI.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}LOCK@{ub}

@{b}About...@{ub}
     This will bring up an `About' requester with some information
     about MirrorManager and its authors.

@{b}Quit@{ub}
     This will terminate MirrorManager.  If your configuration has
     changed since you last saved it you will have to confirm a
     requester to actually quit MirrorManager.

          @{i}Note:@{ui} MirrorManager will not quit under the following
          circumstances:
             - There are some open filerequester

             - The application is locked

             - There are still some ARexx commands running

The @{b}Edit@{ub} Menu
=============

@{b}Add@{ub}
     This will add an entry at the bottom of the listview.  The initial
     name of the new entry is set to @{b}- UNNAMED -@{ub}, the command and
     argument fields are emtpy.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}ADD@{ub}

@{b}Insert@{ub}
     This will insert an entry into the listview at cursorposition.
     The initial name of the new entry is set to @{b}- UNNAMED -@{ub}, the
     command and argument fields are emtpy.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}INSERT@{ub}

@{b}Clone@{ub}
     This will make an identical copy of the currently active entry at
     cursorposition.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}CLONE@{ub}

@{b}Remove@{ub}
     This will delete the currently active entry in the listview and
     activate its successor.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}REMOVE@{ub}

@{b}Edit...@{ub}
     This will bring up a new window where you are able to edit a
     listview entry.  As long as the `Edit Window' is open the `Main
     Window' is busy.

     An entry is split into three parts:
        - The name of the entry appearing in the listview.

        - The command which has to be an ARexx script or inline code.

        - The arguments for the command.  If you specify inline code in
          the command field the argument field is ignored.

@{b}Clear@{ub}
     This will remove all entries from the listview and unset the
     internal @{b}CONFIGNAME@{ub} variable.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}CLEAR@{ub}

@{b}Sort@{ub}
     This will perform a case insensitive sort on the entries in the
     listview.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}SORT@{ub}

@{b}Top@{ub}
     This will move the currently active entry to the beginning of the
     listview.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}TOP@{ub}

@{b}Up@{ub}
     This will move the currently active entry in the listview one line
     up.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}UP@{ub}

@{b}Down@{ub}
     This will move the currently active entry in the listview one line
     down.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}DOWN@{ub}

@{b}Bottom@{ub}
     This will move the currently active entry to the end of the
     listview.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}BOTTOM@{ub}

The @{b}Output@{ub} Menu
===============

@{b}Open Window@{ub}
     This will open the `Working Window', the window into which
     MirrorManager's ARexx scripts print their information.

@{b}Clear Window@{ub}
     This will clear the contents of the `Working Window'.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}MESSAGE@{ub}

@{b}Save Log...@{ub}
     This will bring up a filerequester asking you for a filename under
     which you would like to save the contents of the `Working Window'.

     See also: ARexx command @{b}SAVELOG@{ub}


@EndNode

@Node "ARexx Scripts" "MirrorManager.guide/ARexx Scripts"
@Next "ARexx Commands"
@Prev "Menu Items"
@Toc "Main"

ARexx Scripts
*************

All ARexx scripts coming with MirrorManager expect their arguments
introduced by a keyword which must be seperated from the argument value
by one or more Space characters.

For example,
     rx MakeTree.rexx FROM "treefile" TO "pathname"

is the correct way to run @{b}MakeTree.rexx@{ub} which has the template
@{b}FROM/K/A,TO/A@{ub}

     @{i}Caution:@{ui} Legal keywords for each command are listed here in
     @{b}ReadArgs()@{ub} template style.  There is however a difference between
     the way @{b}ReadArgs()@{ub} parses the arguments and the way we do.

     For example,
          rx MakeTree.rexx FROM="treefile" TO="pathname"

     would be legal for @{b}ReadArgs()@{ub} but it is @{i}not@{ui} legal for the ARexx
     scripts listed here.  The @{b}=@{ub} is not a legal keyword/value delimiter
     for ARexx.

There are @{b}.rexx@{ub} and @{b}.mm@{ub} script files coming with the MirrorManager
distibution

@{b}.rexx@{ub}
     script files are absolutely @{i}independent@{ui} and do never address to the
     MirrorManager's GUI application.  This means that you can execute
     them from a CLI/Shell, configure them for a use with Stefan
     Becker's ToolManager, or install them on any directory management
     application.

@{b}.mm@{ub}
     script files need the MirrorManager MUI application.  They depend
     on the way the GUI passes arguments to it's ARexx scripts and they
     heavily use the ARexx commands offered by the MUI application.

     In addition to the options listed below, @{b}.mm@{ub} scripts usually know
     a switch @{b}AUTO/S@{ub}.  Last can be used to force a closing of the
     message window after the script has completed.


 @{" MirrorManager Scripts " Link "MirrorManager Scripts"}    Verbose documentation on all supplied script files
 @{" Calling Method " Link "Calling Method"}           How MirrorManager executes ARexx code
 @{" Hints " Link "Hints"}                    Hints for writing new scripts for MirrorManager


@EndNode

@Node "MirrorManager Scripts" "MirrorManager.guide/MirrorManager Scripts"
@Next "Calling Method"
@Toc "ARexx Scripts"

MirrorManager ARexx Scripts
===========================

@{b}MakeTree @{b}FROM/K/A,TO/A,NOCREATE/S@{ub}@{ub}
     @{b}MakeTree.rexx@{ub} creates all directories listed in the given @{b}FROM@{ub}
     file relative to a given @{b}TO@{ub} directory.  The directory structure
     and a comment for each directory will be taken from that @{b}FROM@{ub}
     file, which is usually called @{b}TREE@{ub} in case of the Aminet.

     The @{b}TREE@{ub} file will be scanned top-down and line by line, empty
     lines are ignored as well as lines beginning with a @{b}#@{ub} character.
     The first word (i.e.  everything upto the first white space) in
     each line will be taken as the direcory name, the rest of the line
     will be added as a filenote to the directory.

     For example, executing @{b}rx MakeTree.rexx FROM tree TO a:b@{ub} with the
     file @{b}TREE@{ub} looking somewhat like this

          # All directories on Aminet
          
          new          Upload area
          recent       Files uploaded the last seven days
          biz          Business software
          biz/cad      Computer aided design
          ...

     creates the directories @{b}a:b/new@{ub}, @{b}a:b/recent@{ub}, ...  adding the
     filenotes (comments) @{b}Upload area@{ub}, ... respectively.

          @{i}Caution:@{ui} @{b}MakeTree.rexx@{ub} is smart enough to create a path @{b}a:b/c@{ub}
          by creating the directory @{b}a:b@{ub} before creating @{b}a:b/c@{ub}.
          However, @{b}a:@{ub} must be legal of course.

     Using the option keyword @{b}NOCREATE@{ub} will add filenotes for existing
     directories only.  You might prefer this behaviour if you don't
     use to keep a complete Aminet hierarchy and @{b}CleanupIncoming@{ub} or
     @{b}ExamineIndex@{ub} created new directories.

     @{b}MakeTree.rexx@{ub} needs the AmigaDOS commands @{b}MakeDir@{ub} and @{b}FileNote@{ub}
     (and optionally @{b}RequestFile@{ub} and @{b}Delete@{ub}) available in your command
     searchpath.

@{b}CutTree @{b}PATH/A@{ub}@{ub}
     @{b}CutTree@{ub} deletes empty directories in the given path.  I usually
     don't keep a complete Aminet directory hierarchy because many of
     them stay empty anyway and scanning them for new files

@{b}SplitIndex @{b}FROM/K/A,TO/K/A@{ub}@{ub}
     @{b}SplitIndex@{ub} splits given @{b}FROM@{ub} index file into several smaller files
     combining those which begin with the same character.  With the @{b}TO@{ub}
     parameter you can specify a `stem' for the filenames; the first
     character which they have in comon will be appended to it as a
     suffix.

     The @{b}CleanupIncoming@{ub} script supports these kind of index files and
     the benefit in performance compared to non-splitted index files is
     great!

@{b}MakeIndex @{b}FROM/K/A,TO/A@{ub}@{ub}
     @{b}MakeIndex@{ub} is ment to create a local Aminet mirror index.  In
     general it creates a list of all files available in a given path
     including file size and file comment.

          @{i}Caution:@{ui} Due to a problem with @{b}pragma('D')@{ub} you @{i}must@{ui} execute
          this script using @{b}RX@{ub} explicitly - even in the WShell.

     This ARexx script needs the AmigaDOS commands @{b}List@{ub} and @{b}Sort@{ub}
     available in your path.

@{b}ExamineIndex @{b}FILE/K/A,WITH/K/A,PATH/K,MOVE/S,COMMENT/S,MAKEPATH/S,FAST/S@{ub}@{ub}
     In general, @{b}ExamineIndex@{ub} compares your two index files.  (e.g.
     your @{b}LOCAL@{ub} index and an original Aminet @{b}INDEX@{ub} file.)

     blabla...

          @{i}Hacker's Note:@{ui} A great speed improvement can be made by using
          the @{b}agrep@{ub} command instead of Commodore's @{b}Search@{ub} command.
          Please take a closer look at the procedure @{b}searchcmd@{ub} in
          @{b}ExamineIndex.mm@{ub} and/or @{b}ExamineIndex.rexx@{ub} respectively and
          replace the @{b}return 'Search ...@{ub} line by the following:
               return 'agrep > "'tempinfo'"' '"'pattern'"' '"'file'"'

@{b}SortIndex @{b}FROM/K/A,FILE/S,DIR/S,QUICK/S,AUTO/S@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}SortIndex@{ub} script allows you to sort a given @{b}FROM@{ub} file by
     either filename or directory name.

@{b}CleanupIncoming @{b}FROM/K/A,TO/K,WITH=INDEX/K/A,MOVE/S,COPY/S,@{ub} @{b}NOCOMMENT/S,MAKEPATH/S,REPLACE/S,FAST/S,REMAP/K@{ub}@{ub}
     @{b}CleanupIncoming@{ub} examines (non-recursively) the files in your
     @{b}incoming:@{ub} directory and looks them up in an Aminet mirror @{b}INDEX@{ub}
     file.  For each file in your @{b}incoming:@{ub} directory which is listed
     exactly @{i}once@{ui} in the Aminet index file the following actions can be
     performed:

        - A filenote (comment) can be added according to the one listed
          in your Aminet index file and

        - The file can be copied (or moved) to the location listed in
          the Aminet index.

     The Aminet directory hierarchy can be created using the @{b}MakeTree@{ub}
     script.

     @{b}CleanupIncoming.rexx@{ub} needs the AmigaDOS commands @{b}List@{ub}, @{b}Sort@{ub},
     @{b}Search@{ub}, @{b}Filenote@{ub}, @{b}Copy@{ub} and @{b}Delete@{ub} available in your path.

          @{i}Hacker's Note:@{ui} A great speed improvement can be made by using
          the @{b}agrep@{ub} command instead of Commodore's @{b}Search@{ub} command.
          Please take a closer look at the procedure @{b}searchcmd@{ub} in
          @{b}CleanupIncoming.mm@{ub} and/or @{b}CleanupIncoming.rexx@{ub} respectively
          and replace the @{b}return 'Search ...@{ub} line by the following:
               return 'agrep > "'tempinfo'"' '"'pattern'"' '"'file'"'

@{b}MirrorManager.rexx@{ub}
     The file @{b}MirrorManager.rexx@{ub} is the configuration file for the
     @{b}MirrorManager@{ub} MUI application.  @{b}MirrorManager.rexx@{ub} will be
     executed by it's host on startup when the ToolType or CLI option
     @{b}CONFIGNAME=rexx/MirrorManager.rexx@{ub} was set.  On the other hand if
     @{b}MirrorManager.rexx@{ub} was executed via @{b}RX@{ub} or by double-clicking on
     it's icon and no empty application is running then it tries to run
     it's own MirrorManager executable.  If you want to write your own
     configuration scripts then you should see @{"Hints" Link "Hints"}, for details.

     To set-up path and filenames in @{b}MirrorManager.rexx@{ub} you should use
     the configure script, which can be found in the
     @{b}MirrorManager/rexx/@{ub} directory.  See @{"Using Configure" Link "Using Configure"}, for
     further details.

@{b}Demo.rexx@{ub}
     The @{b}Demo.rexx@{ub} script demonstrates the use of the GUI's ARexx
     interface.  You should execute this demo either via
     double-clicking on its icon or by loading it as a @{i}configuration@{ui}
     via @{b}Project/Load@{ub}.  The actions performed by @{b}Demo.rexx@{ub} are fully
     self-explaining and need no further documentation here.  @{b}:)@{ub}

@{b}whoami.rexx@{ub}
     This script resolves the own path and filename.  We decided to
     include this scriptfile as a tutorial example because it is quite
     a difficult task to do this correctly.

     Currently the @{b}PARSE SOURCE@{ub} instruction is limited to a length of
     64 characters.  This is an enormous problem since this makes it
     impossible for an ARexx script to resolve its pathname if it is
     located deeper in the directory hierarchy.  We have reported this
     bug, but we did not receive a reply yet.


@EndNode

@Node "ARexx Commands" "MirrorManager.guide/ARexx Commands"
@Next "Additional Tools"
@Prev "ARexx Scripts"
@Toc "Main"

ARexx Commands
**************

MirrorManager is fully ARexx based and everything it does can be
controled via ARexx.

Since MirrorManager is a MUI application, it offers the default
commands which are understood by every MUI program.  Every MUI
application is able to receive commands via the built-in ARexx port.
(For more information about MUI see @{"MUI" Link "MUI"})


 @{" MUI Built-In ARexx Commands " Link "MUI Built-In ARexx Commands"} 
 @{" MUI Error Codes " Link "MUI Error Codes"} 
 @{" MirrorManager ARexx Commands " Link "MirrorManager ARexx Commands"} 

If you want to write your own ARexx script files for MirrorManager you
should also read @{"Hints" Link "Hints"}.


@EndNode

@Node "MUI Built-In ARexx Commands" "MirrorManager.guide/MUI Built-In ARexx Commands"
@Next "MUI Error Codes"
@Toc "ARexx Commands"

MUI Built-In ARexx Commands
===========================

@{b}QUIT @{b}@{ub}@{ub}
     Ends the application.

     The behaviour of this command is very much like clicking the
     closing Gadget of the application or pressing RCommand-Q or ESC.

@{b}HIDE@{ub}
     Hides (iconifies) the MirrorManager application.  This will
     normally bring up the application icon @{b}MirrorManager.info@{ub} or - if
     this is non-existant - @{b}def_MUI.info@{ub} which will be loaded from
     @{b}env:sys/@{ub}.  This can however be customized with the MUI Preferences
     program.

@{b}SHOW@{ub}
     Shows (pops up) the iconified MirrorManager application.

@{b}INFO @{b}ITEM/A@{ub}@{ub}
     According to the given @{b}ITEM@{ub} parameter the result string is filled
     with the following contents:

    @{b}TITLE@{ub}
          Title of the application (I.e. @{b}MirrorManager@{ub})

    @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
          Author of the  application

    @{b}COPYRIGHT@{ub}
          Copyright message

    @{b}DESCRIPTION@{ub}
          Short description

    @{b}VERSION@{ub}
          Version string

    @{b}BASE@{ub}
          Name of the ARexx port

    @{b}SCREEN@{ub}
          Name of the public screen

     For example,

          OPTIONS RESULTS
          ADDRESS 'MIRRORMANAGER.1'
          
          'INFO Title';       SAY "Application title .......:" result
          'INFO Author';      SAY "Author of the application:" result
          'INFO Copyright';   SAY "Copyright message .......:" result
          'INFO Description'; SAY "Short description .......:" result
          'INFO Version';     SAY "Version string ..........:" result
          'INFO Base';        SAY "Name of the ARexx port ..:" result
          'INFO Screen';      SAY "Name of the pub screen ..:" result

@{b}HELP @{b}FILE/A@{ub}@{ub}
     A list of all ARexx commands available for the application is
     written into the given file.  In addition to the default commands
     MirrorManager supports many application specific commands.  The
     help list will contain these commands as well.

     For example,
          ADDRESS 'MIRRORMANAGER.1'; HELP "ram:help.out"

     creates the file @{b}ram:help.out@{ub} with the following contents:
          Standard-Commands:
          
          Command        Template
          -------        --------
          quit
          hide
          show
          info           ITEM/A
          help           FILE/A
          
          
          Commands for application "MirrorManager":
          
          Command        Template
          -------        --------
          sort
          clear
          numentries
          add            NAME/A,COMMAND/A,ARGS
          clone          NAME
          remove         NAME
          rename         NAME/A
          execute        NAME
          activate       NAME
          up             NAME
          down           NAME
          top            NAME
          bottom         NAME
          load           FILE
          save           FILE
          configname     FILE
          appstart       COMMAND
          message        CLEAR/S,OPEN/S,CLOSE/S,STRING
          complete       PERCENTAGE/N
          working        STRING
          requestchoice  TITLE/K,GADGETS/A,BODY/A
          requestfile    DRAWER,FILE/K,TITLE/K,SAVEMODE/S,DRAWERSONLY/S,NOICONS/S
          savelog        FILE
          lock           ON/S,OFF/S


@EndNode

@Node "MUI Error Codes" "MirrorManager.guide/MUI Error Codes"
@Next "MirrorManager ARexx Commands"
@Prev "MUI Built-In ARexx Commands"
@Toc "ARexx Commands"

MUI Error Codes
===============

In case of an error, MUI returns the following values to the rexx
script:

@{b}-1@{ub}
     Wrong command definition in host program.  (Should never happen.)

@{b}-2@{ub}
     Out of memory.

@{b}-3@{ub}
     Unknown ARexx command.

@{b}-4@{ub}
     Syntax error.

If any of MirrorManager's own ARexx commands fail then either one of
the above or @{b}1@{ub} will be returned.  In general: A value @{b}rc ~= 0@{ub} @{i}always@{ui}
indicates an error.


@EndNode

@Node "MirrorManager ARexx Commands" "MirrorManager.guide/MirrorManager ARexx Commands"
@Prev "MUI Error Codes"
@Toc "ARexx Commands"

MirrorManager ARexx Commands
============================

@{b}SORT@{ub}
     The @{b}SORT@{ub} command performs a case insensitive sort on the
     MirrorManager's listview.  If @{b}SORT@{ub} is called on an already sorted
     listview then identically named entries will be exchanged.

     Calling this function via ARexx has the same result as pressing
     RCommand-S.

@{b}CLEAR@{ub}
     The @{b}CLEAR@{ub} command removes all items from the MirrorManager's
     listview and it will unset the internal @{b}CONFIGNAME@{ub} variable.  As a
     consequence @{b}NUMENTRIES@{ub} will return @{b}result = 0@{ub} after this action
     has been performed.  This can also be achieved by pressing
     RCommand-/.

@{b}NUMENTRIES@{ub}
     Returns the number of items in the MirrorManager's listview.

     For example,
          ADDRESS 'MIRRORMANAGER.1'
          OPTIONS RESULTS
          
          NUMENTRIES
          SAY 'There are currently' result 'items'

@{b}ADD @{b}NAME/A,COMMAND/A,ARGS@{ub}@{ub}
     Creates a new entry and adds it to the @{i}bottom@{ui} of the listview.
     The contents of the @{b}NAME@{ub} field will appear in the MirrorManager's
     listview, @{b}COMMAND@{ub} must contain the pathname of an ARexx program
     and @{b}ARGS@{ub} are the arguments for this ARexx program.

     For example,
          ADDRESS 'MIRRORMANAGER.1'
          ADD '"Add filenotes to INCOMING"',
              '"rexx/CleanupIncoming.mm"',
              '"FROM incoming: WITH aminet:INDEX"'

     will add an item @{b}Add filenotes to INCOMING@{ub} which calls
     @{b}CleanupIncoming.mm@{ub} with arguments @{b}FROM incoming: WITH aminet:INDEX@{ub}.

     Note that all the commata @{b},@{ub} in the above example are ARexx line
     continuation tokens.  They must be removed if the @{b}ADD@{ub} command is
     used in one single line.

     When pressing RCommand-A a new item will be added to the listview.
     The new item will be named @{b}- UNNAMED -@{ub} by default and can be
     edited pressing RCommand-E.

     New items will always become the active item of the listview.

     You may also write ARexx inline code into the @{b}COMMAND@{ub} field.  The
     @{b}ARGS@{ub} field should however be empty then.

     For example,
          ADDRESS 'MIRRORMANAGER.1'
          ADD '"Edit current config"',
              '"*"OPTIONS RESULTS; CONFIGNAME;',
              ' ADDRESS COMMAND ''Ed'' result*""'

     will start an Editor @{b}Ed@{ub} with the name of the current configuration
     script as argument.

     See @{"Calling Method" Link "Calling Method"}, for more information about how MirrorManager
     executes ARexx code.

@{b}CLONE @{b}NAME@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}CLONE@{ub} command makes an identical copy of an item in the
     listview.  If no name is given, then the active item will be
     cloned.  The new item will be inserted directly before the
     original item in the list and it will become active.  (1)

     @{b}CLONE@{ub} can be called via RCommand-C.

@{b}REMOVE @{b}NAME@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}REMOVE@{ub} command deletes an item from the listview.  If no name
     is given then the active item will be removed.  @{b}REMOVE@{ub} activates
     the next item if there is a next one, otherwise, if the removed
     item was the last in the list then its previous item (which now is
     the last item) will become active.

     For example,
          ADDRESS 'MIRRORMANAGER.1'
          
          REMOVE '"Edit current config"'

     removes the item in the above example.  This operation is
     identical to pressing RCommand-X.

@{b}RENAME @{b}NAME/A@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}RENAME@{ub} command changes the name of the active item to the
     given one.  This operation will only redraw the active line in the
     listview.  Renaming the current item can also be done by editing
     this item either by pressing RCommand-E or selecting @{b}Edit/Edit...@{ub}
     from the menu.

@{b}EXECUTE @{b}NAME@{ub}@{ub}
     Executes a command by the name of its entry in the listview.  If
     no name is given then the active item's command will be executed.

     @{b}EXECUTE@{ub} can also be performed by double-clicking or pressing the
     Return key on the desired item.

@{b}ACTIVATE @{b}NAME@{ub}@{ub}
     @{b}ACTIVATE@{ub} highlights a listview item and makes it become the active
     item.  If no name is given then @{b}ACTIVATE@{ub} returns the name of the
     active item.  Otherwise the command behind the given item will be
     returned.

     For example,
          OPTIONS RESULTS
          ADDRESS 'MIRRORMANAGER.1'
          
          ACTIVATE; name = result
          
          IF rc ~= 0 THEN SAY 'There is currently no active item.'
                     ELSE DO
                       ACTIVATE '"' || name || '"'; cmd = result
                       SAY name 'performs the following command:' cmd
                       END

@{b}UP @{b}NAME@{ub}@{ub}
     Moves a listview item one line up.  If no name is given then the
     active item will be moved.  This operation is identical to
     pressing RCommand-U.

     For example,
          OPTIONS RESULTS
          ADDRESS 'MIRRORMANAGER.1'
          
          UP; pos= result
          
          IF rc = 0 THEN DO WHILE pos > 0
            'UP'; pos= result
            END
          ELSE SAY 'There is currently no item active.'

     would be a straight forward implementation of the @{b}TOP@{ub} command.

@{b}DOWN @{b}NAME@{ub}@{ub}
     Moves a listview item one line down.  If no name is given then the
     active item will be moved.  This operation is identical to
     pressing RCommand-D.

@{b}TOP @{b}NAME@{ub}@{ub}
     Moves an item to the beginning of the listview.  If no name is
     given then the active item will be moved.  This operation is
     identical to pressing RCommand-T.

@{b}BOTTOM @{b}NAME@{ub}@{ub}
     Moves an item to the end of the listview.  If no name is given
     then the active item will be moved.  This operation is identical
     to pressing RCommand-B.

@{b}LOAD @{b}FILE@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}LOAD@{ub} command executes a configuration file.  If called without
     arguments the last configuration will be re-loaded.

@{b}SAVE @{b}FILE@{ub}@{ub}
     @{b}SAVE@{ub} writes an ARexx executable to disk which, when executed
     restores the current MirrorManager configuration.  If no filename
     is passed then the @{b}.rexx@{ub} file will be written with the current
     default name.

     The @{b}SAVE@{ub} command is identical to selecing @{b}Project/Save@{ub} from the
     menu.  You cannot write back the current configuration via a
     single keypress.  Pressing RCommand-W will pop-up a filerequester
     asking you for the filename to write to.

@{b}CONFIGNAME @{b}FILE@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}CONFIGNAME@{ub} command sets the current filename for the
     configuration script.  If called without parameters, @{b}CONFIGNAME@{ub}
     will return the current filename.

     The config filename will be set always after loading a
     configuration via @{b}Project/Load@{ub} or after saving via @{b}Project/Save
     as...@{ub}.  It will also be set if these actions are performed via the
     ARexx commands @{b}LOAD@{ub} or @{b}SAVE@{ub} respectively.

     If MirrorManager has been run by executing a configuration
     scriptfile then this scriptfile will set @{b}CONFIGNAME@{ub} to its own
     name.  Otherwise, if MirrorManager has been started by
     double-clicking its icon then @{b}CONFIGNAME@{ub} will be taken from the
     ToolTypes.  When started from the CLI/Shell then the startup
     @{b}CONFIGNAME@{ub} can be given via

          1> MirrorManager CONFIGNAME=rexx/myconfig.mm

          @{i}Caution:@{ui} If MirrorManager is executed without specifying
          @{b}CONFIGNAME@{ub} then it will be @{i}unset@{ui}!  This is so because the
          configuration scripts run MirrorManager without any arguments
          and of course they don't want MirrorManager to execute another
          configuration script.  In this case @{b}Project/Save@{ub} will behave
          like @{b}Project/Save as...@{ub} and open a file requester.

@{b}APPSTART @{b}COMMAND@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}APPSTART@{ub} command sets the default command sequence for running
     MirrorManager.  If no arguments are given then the current default will
     be returned.

     @{b}APPSTART@{ub} can be set via a ToolType called @{b}APPSTART=<command
     sequence>@{ub}.  The default is @{b}Run MirrorManager@{ub}.

@{b}MESSAGE @{b}CLEAR/S,OPEN/S,CLOSE/S,STRING@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}MESSAGE@{ub} command prints the given string in the MirrorManager
     working window appending a new line to the current window contents.
     Calling @{b}MESSAGE@{ub} without parameters is a no-op.

    @{b}MESSAGE CLEAR@{ub}
          wipes out the contents of the working window

    @{b}MESSAGE OPEN@{ub}
          opens the working window

    @{b}MESSAGE CLOSE@{ub}
          closes the working window

     Given string will be appended to the window contents even if the
     working window is closed at the time MirrorManager recieves the
     @{b}MESSAGE@{ub} command.

@{b}COMPLETE @{b}PERCENTAGE/N@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}COMPLETE@{ub} command sets the gauge in the MirrorManager working
     window to the given value which has to be between 0 and 100.  If
     @{b}COMPLETE@{ub} is called without any parameters it will set the result
     string to the current gauge level.  Even if the working window is
     closed at the time MirrorManager recieves the @{b}COMPLETE@{ub} command,
     the gauge will be set to the given value.

@{b}WORKING @{b}STRING@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}WORKING@{ub} command sets the title of the MirrorManager working
     window to the given string.  If it is called without any argument,
     @{b}WORKING@{ub} returns the current window title in the result string.

@{b}REQUESTCHOICE @{b}TITLE/K,GADGETS/A,BODY/A@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}REQUESTCHOICE@{ub} command is similar to the Commodore
     @{b}RequestChoice@{ub} program.  This gives the possibility to interact
     with the user.  @{b}REQUESTCHOICE@{ub} opens a MUI-Requester which can be
     configured using

    @{b}TITLE@{ub}
          Title for the requester window. Defaults to @{b}MirrorManager@{ub}.

    @{b}GADGETS@{ub}
          Pointer to a string containing the possible answers.  The
          format looks like @{b}_Save|_Use|_Test|_Cancel@{ub}.  If you precede
          an entry with a @{b}*@{ub}, this answer will become the active object.
          Pressing Return will terminate the requester with this
          response.  A underscore @{b}_@{ub} character indicates the keyboard
          shortcut for this response.

    @{b}BODY@{ub}
          The requester's body text

     The gadget and body string is parsed by MUI's text engine so it
     may contain the special characters

    @{b}\n@{ub}
          Start a new line. With this character you can e.g. create
          multi line buttons.

    @{b}ESC -@{ub}
          Disable text engine, following chars will be printed without
          further parsing.

    @{b}ESC u@{ub}
          Set the soft style to underline.

    @{b}ESC b@{ub}
          Set the soft style to bold.

    @{b}ESC i@{ub}
          Set the soft style to italic.

    @{b}ESC n@{ub}
          Set the soft style back to normal.

    @{b}ESC <n>@{ub}
          Use pen number n (2..9) as front pen. n must be a valid
          DrawInfo pen as specified in @{b}intuition/screens.h@{ub}.

    @{b}ESC c@{ub}
          Center current (and following) line(s).  This sequence is
          only valid at the beginning of a string or after a newline
          character.

    @{b}ESC r@{ub}
          Right justify current (and following) line(s).  This sequence
          is only valid at the beginning of a string or after a newline
          character.

    @{b}ESC l@{ub}
          Left justify current (and following) line(s).  This sequence
          is only valid at the beginning of a string or after a newline
          character.

    @{b}ESC I[s]@{ub}
          Draw MUI image with specification <s>.  See autodocs of image
          class for image spec definition.

     a quick example:

          OPTIONS RESULTS
          ADDRESS 'MIRRORMANAGER.1'
          
          REQUESTCHOICE TITLE "Dolle Sache" "_Yep!" "*Ec*EbMUI*En*Nis magic"

@{b}REQUESTFILE @{b}DRAWER,FILE/K,TITLE/K,SAVEMODE/S,DRAWERSONLY/S,NOICONS/S@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}REQUESTFILE@{ub} command ...

@{b}SAVELOG @{b}FILE@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}SAVELOG@{ub} command ...

@{b}LOCK @{b}ON/S,OFF/S@{ub}@{ub}
     The @{b}LOCK@{ub} command blafasel ...

---------- Footnotes ----------

(1)  This is a lie.  To be honest: The new item will be added directly
below the original entry.  The active item remains unchanged.


@EndNode

@Node "Calling Method" "MirrorManager.guide/Calling Method"
@Next "Hints"
@Prev "MirrorManager Scripts"
@Toc "ARexx Scripts"

How MirrorManager Executes ARexx Code
=====================================

If you double-click one of MirrorManager's listview items, MirrorManager
will examine the @{b}Command@{ub} and @{b}Arguments@{ub} field associated with the
selected item.

ARexx Inline Code
-----------------

If the contents of the @{b}Command@{ub} field begins with a double quote @{b}"@{ub} then
MirrorManager expects this to be inline code and executes it like the
ARexx starter command @{b}RX@{ub} would.  The only difference to @{b}RX@{ub} is that the
default host is set to the MirrorManager's ARexx port and the default
extension for external ARexx scripts is @{b}.mm@{ub}.

ARexx Script Files
------------------

On the other hand, if the contents of the @{b}Command@{ub} field does not begin
with a double quote then the contents is expected to be the (path and)
filename of an ARexx script.  The pathname should be given relative to
the path of the MirrorManager MUI application.  However, also absolute
pathnames are possible.

     @{i}Caution:@{ui} You must not quote the contents of the @{b}Command@{ub} field
     unless it is ment as ARexx inline code!  MirrorManager will be
     able to execute your script file even if the path and/or the
     filename contains spaces.

Before executing an ARexx script MirrorManager will generate inline
code on its own.

Consider the following example:

Name
     @{b}Add filenotes to INCOMING@{ub}

Command
     @{b}Ram Disk:MirrorManager/rexx/CleanupIncoming.mm@{ub}

Arguments
     @{b}FROM "Ram Disk:incoming" WITH "aminet:INDEX"@{ub}

After setting the default host for ARexx to the name of MirrorManager's
ARexx port, MirrorManager will execute the following inline code in
order to invoke @{b}CleanupIncoming.mm@{ub}:

     "CALL 'Ram Disk:MirrorManager/rexx/CleanupIncoming.mm',
           'FROM','Ram Disk:incoming','WITH','aminet:INDEX'"

Double quotes inside the @{b}Arguments@{ub} field are treated as you would expect
that for ordinary Shell commands.  I.e. A double quote inside a double
quoted argument needs a leading asterisk @{b}*@{ub}.

For example,

     "a *quote* *" inside"

An asterisk however does not need to be prefixed by another asterisk.

Here is an overview how MirrorManager converts the contents of the
@{b}Arguments@{ub} field which is shown on the left hand side of the following
table:

           a b c         'a','b','c'
           a "b c"       'a','b c'
           a"b           'a""b'
           a'b           'a''b'
           "a*"b"        'a""b'
           "a'b"         'a''b'
           "a""b"        'a','b'

Consider the source code @{b}rxcallstr.c@{ub} for verbose documentation and
further details.

As you can see in the above example, MirrorManager will pass the
arguments to the ARexx script in tokenized form.  From within the ARexx
script one can reach the @{b}i@{ub}-th argument with @{b}arg(i)@{ub}.  The ARexx variable
@{b}arg()@{ub} contains the number of supplied aruments.  This is identical to
an invocation method of ARexx scripts with @{b}RXFB_TOKEN@{ub} set.  And it is
much more convenient for the ARexx programmer because he doesn't need to
parse an argument string on his own.


@EndNode

@Node "Hints" "MirrorManager.guide/Hints"
@Prev "Calling Method"
@Toc "ARexx Scripts"

Hints For Writing New ARexx Scripts For MirrorManager
=====================================================

Before writing ARexx scripts for MirrorManager you've got to make up
your mind if you want to make it GUI-dependent or if your script file
should better be executable from within any environment.


 @{" GUI-Dependent " Link "GUI-Dependent"} 
 @{" GUI-Independent " Link "GUI-Independent"} 


@EndNode

@Node "GUI-Dependent" "MirrorManager.guide/GUI-Dependent"
@Next "GUI-Independent"
@Toc "Hints"

Writing GUI-Dependent ARexx Scripts
-----------------------------------

Programming the GUI's ARexx interface will most often be done in order
to configure MirrorManager to your own digests.  If your work should
however be useful for a greater variety of MirrorManager users then you
should keep in mind the following:

  1. MirrorManager has @{i}no@{ui} assignments and needs @{i}no@{ui} environment
     variables.  You should therefore never write MirrorManager
     configuration scripts depending on your environment and your
     assignments.  Instead you should take advantage of the fact that
     MirrorManager guarantees the current directory for all @{b}.mm@{ub} scripts
     to be the directory MirrorManager resides in.  And usually the
     sub-directory @{b}rexx/@{ub} contains these @{b}.mm@{ub} scripts.

  2. An important part of your configuration script makes up finding a
     legal host.  The following example demonstrates how to do this
     poperly:

          /*
          **  Finding a MirrorManager host
          */
          
          portbase = 'MIRRORMANAGER.'
          portlist = SHOW('P',,'0A'X)
          
          OPTIONS RESULTS
          DO WHILE WORDS(portlist) > 0
            PARSE VAR portlist portname '0A'X portlist
            IF COMPARE(portname,portbase) = LENGTH(portbase)+1 THEN DO
              ADDRESS(portname); 'NUMENTRIES'
              IF result = 0 THEN portlist= ""
                            ELSE ADDRESS
              END
            END
          
          IF ADDRESS() ~= portname THEN DO
            SAY 'MirrorManager is not running... exiting...'
            EXIT
            END
          
          /* ... */
          
          EXIT

  3. ARexx filenames containing spaces are currently somewhat difficult
     to execute.  They are no problem for MirrorManager but they seem
     to be for several other hosts.  Even @{b}RX@{ub} needs a double quoted
     ToolType value for @{b}CMD@{ub}, for example

          CMD="my script.rexx"

     or a kludge for executing @{b}my script.rexx@{ub} from within the Shell:

          RX "call 'my example.rexx'"

  4. If your configuration script should be executable from outside the
     GUI then you @{i}must@{ui} set your own name to the application via the
     @{b}CONFIGNAME@{ub} command.  Otherwise @{b}CONFIGNAME@{ub} will either be @{i}unset@{ui} and
     calling @{b}SAVE@{ub} without a parameter would fail, or if @{b}CONFIGNAME@{ub} was
     set then @{b}SAVE@{ub} would overwrite the old configuration.

     In fact it is not easy to determine the own full pathname from
     within an ARexx script, so here is an example

          PARSE SOURCE . . s
          
          t= LEFT(s,LASTPOS(':',s))
          called= STRIP( LEFT(t,LASTPOS(' ',t)) )
          
          CALL PRAGMA('W','N')
          DO WHILE ~EXISTS(called) & LASTPOS(' ',called) > 0
            called= LEFT(called,LASTPOS(' ',called)-1)
            END
          
          IF LEFT(cr,1) = 'R' THEN DO
            host= ADDRESS()
            PARSE VAR s (called) s (host) .
          
            resolved= STRIP(s)
          
            CALL PRAGMA('W','N')
            DO WHILE ~EXISTS(resolved)
              resolved= LEFT(resolved,LASTPOS(' ',resolved)-1)
              END
          
            END
          
          /* ... */

     At the bottom of this example, i.e. after the @{b}/* ... */@{ub} the
     variable @{b}called@{ub} contains the filename used for calling this script
     while @{b}resolved@{ub} contains the expanded path including the root's
     volume name.

     An example procedure @{b}whoami@{ub} can also be found in the @{b}rexx/@{ub} drawer
     coming with MirrorManager.  See @{"MirrorManager Scripts" Link "MirrorManager Scripts"}, @{b}whoami.rexx@{ub}
     for more information.

  5. You should always test the result of a call.  All of the GUI's
     ARexx commands return 0 in the @{b}rc@{ub} variable if they have been
     successful.  A value @{b}~= 0@{ub} @{i}always@{ui} indicates an error.  See
     @{"MUI Error Codes" Link "MUI Error Codes"}, for details on error codes.

  6. Strings passed to the GUI always have to be quoted twice if they
     contain any white space.  Additionally, double quotes @{b}"@{ub} and
     asterisks @{b}*@{ub} in a string passed to the GUI have to be escaped with
     an asterisk @{b}*@{ub} to @{b}*"@{ub} and @{b}**@{ub} respectively.  For this reason it is
     often useful to implement a function that quotes a string for you.

     For example,
          /* translate '"' into '*"' and '*' into '**' */
          
          transquote: PROCEDURE
            PARSE ARG s
            t= s
            q= MAX( LASTPOS('*',s), LASTPOS('"',s) )
          
            DO WHILE q > 0
              t= INSERT('*',t,q-1,1)
              s= LEFT(s,q-1)
              q= MAX( LASTPOS('*',s), LASTPOS('"',s) )
              END
          
            RETURN '"' || t || '"'

     double quotes the given argument string and translates each
     occurence of a double quote @{b}"@{ub} into @{b}*"@{ub} and each occurence of @{b}*@{ub} into
     @{b}**@{ub}.  Here is an example for the usage of @{b}transquote@{ub} with the @{b}ADD@{ub}
     command:
          ADDRESS 'MIRRORMANAGER.1'
          
          ADD transquote('Say hello') transquote('"SAY ''Hello world!''"')


@EndNode

@Node "GUI-Independent" "MirrorManager.guide/GUI-Independent"
@Prev "GUI-Dependent"
@Toc "Hints"

Writing GUI-Independent ARexx Scripts
-------------------------------------

The @{b}.rexx@{ub} script files supplied with MirrorManager are all GUI
independent, i.e. they never address to the MirrorManager's GUI host.
This guarantees functionality from within any environment.

The following is recommended to this kind of MirrorManager scripts:

  1. The template for command line arguments sould be available in a
     @{b}ReadArgs()@{ub} style.  Almost any user will expect this kind of
     argument passing meanwhile.  The following example demonstrates a
     convenient argument parsing for a template
     @{b}REQUIRED/K/A,OPTIONAL/K,SWITCH/S@{ub}

          /*
          **  parse command line arguments
          */
          
          required = ""
          optional = ""
          switches = ""
          
          IF ( ARG() < 1 ) | ( (ARG() = 1) & ARG(1)= '?' ) then do
            OPTIONS PROMPT "REQUIRED/A,OPTIONAL,BOOL=SWITCH/S: "
            PARSE PULL ARGS
            END
          ELSE PARSE ARG args
          
          DO WHILE WORDS(args) > 0
            av= next_arg()
            SELECT
              WHEN UPPER(av) = "REQUIRED" then do
                IF WORDS(args) > 0 THEN required= next_arg()
                ELSE DO
                  SAY "missing argument value after REQUIRED keyword"
                  EXIT usage()+5
                  END
                END
          
              WHEN UPPER(av) = "OPTIONAL" THEN DO
                IF WORDS(args) > 0 THEN optional= next_arg()
                ELSE DO
                  SAY "missing arument value after OPTIONAL keyword"
                  EXIT usage()+5
                  END
                END
          
              WHEN (UPPER(av) = "BOOL") | (upper(av) = "SWITCH") then do
                switches = switches || 's'
                END
          
              OTHERWISE DO
                IF av ~= '?' THEN SAY "Unknown keyword" av
                EXIT usage()+5
                END
          
            END /* select */
          
          END /* do */

          IF WORDS(required) < 1 then do
            SAY "required argument missing"
            EXIT usage()+5
            END
          
          /* ... */
          
          IF LASTPOS('s',switches) > 0 THEN DO
             /* what this switch stands for */
             END
          
          /* ... */
          
          next_arg: PROCEDURE EXPOSE args
            args= STRIP(args)
            IF LEFT(args,1) = '"' THEN PARSE VAR args '"' a '"' args
                                  ELSE PARSE VAR args     a     args
            RETURN STRIP(a,'b','"');



@EndNode

@Node "Additional Tools" "MirrorManager.guide/Additional Tools"
@Next "Politics"
@Prev "ARexx Commands"
@Toc "Main"

Additional Tools
****************

MirrorManager comes with a load of extras which obviously can be found
in the @{b}xtras/@{ub} drawer.  In this chapter we'll give you a brief overview
of the tools which are available there and explain what they can do for
you.


 @{" AMM " Link "AMM"}   AminetMirrorManager (adt file parser)
 @{" ALs " Link "ALs"}   Create (ADT) index files from your local mirror
 @{" Ex " Link "Ex"}    Executing shell scripts from a pipe


@EndNode

@Node "AMM" "MirrorManager.guide/AMM"
@Next "ALs"
@Prev "Additional Tools"
@Toc "Additional Tools"

AminetMirrorManager (AMM)
=========================

The @{b}AMM@{ub} tool is a very flexible command which collects files and looks
them up in index files of type @{b}adt-v1@{ub} or @{b}adt-v2@{ub}.  For each match (or
mismatch), @{b}AMM@{ub} can expand some macros in a given scriptfile, so that
executing @{b}AMM@{ub} output can perform various tasks.


 @{" Installing AMM " Link "Installing AMM"}        How to install @{b}AMM@{ub} and the provided scripts
 @{" Options & Switches " Link "Options & Switches"}    How to tell @{b}AMM@{ub} what to do
 @{" Configuring AMM " Link "Configuring AMM"}       How to write @{b}AMM@{ub} scripts for @{i}your@{ui} mirror
 @{" Hints & Tips " Link "Hints & Tips"}          Non-intuitive @{b}:)@{ub} operations


@EndNode

@Node "Installing AMM" "MirrorManager.guide/Installing AMM"
@Next "Options & Switches"
@Prev "AMM"
@Toc "AMM"

Installing AMM
--------------

To install @{b}AMM@{ub} simply copy the executable @{b}amm.000@{ub} (or @{b}amm.030@{ub} if you
have an MC-68030 Amiga) somewhere into your path (e.g. to @{b}C:@{ub}) and
rename it to @{b}amm@{ub}.  For example,
     Copy CLONE amm.000 TO c:amm

Next you should get an Aminet index file of type @{b}adt-v1@{ub} or @{b}adt-v2@{ub}.
These can be obtained (e.g. via @{b}ftp@{ub}) from all Aminet sites in the
@{b}info/adt/@{ub} directory.  If you're using @{b}MUIAdt@{ub} then you will
automatically get the @{b}RECENT.adt@{ub} file each time @{b}MUIAdt@{ub} connects to an
Aminet site.  See @{"Hints & Tips" Link "Hints & Tips"}, for further details.

Now you need some @{b}.amm@{ub} scripts.  These are text files which are
expanded by @{b}AMM@{ub}.  Here is a very simple example:
     "%p%n" lives in "%d"

This (or a similar) example script called @{b}print.amm@{ub} is included in this
distribution, so @{b}AMM@{ub} is now ready for a first example take-off.

@{i}Example:@{ui} Suppose you've downloaded some files from the Aminet into a
directory @{b}incoming:@{ub} and you've also downloaded the @{b}RECENT.adt@{ub} file into
this directory.  Now try out:
     amm -f incoming:RECENT.adt -y print.amm incoming:

@{b}AMM@{ub} will now collect all files in your @{b}incoming:@{ub} directory and for each
file there, which also exists in the index @{b}RECENT.adt@{ub} it will print a
line of the form:
     "incoming:foo.bar" lives in "which/witch"

Note that you don't really need to @{b}uncompress@{ub} the @{b}.Z@{ub} or @{b}.gz@{ub} files to
disk since @{b}AMM@{ub} can read the index file from the standard input stream.
For example,
     zcat ADT_AMINET.gz | amm -y print incoming:

does exactly the same as the example above but with a @{b}gzip@{ub}'ed index
file of type @{b}adt-v2@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Options & Switches" "MirrorManager.guide/Options & Switches"
@Next "Configuring AMM"
@Prev "Installing AMM"
@Toc "AMM"

Arguments, Options & Switches
-----------------------------

Before @{b}AMM@{ub} starts reading the index file, it collects all items in the
command line.  @{b}AMM@{ub} distinguishes between, tree types of arguments:
@{i}filenames@{ui}
     Ordinaly filenames are inserted into @{b}AMM@{ub}'s internal search tree
     for a later lookup in the index file.

@{i}directories@{ui}
     @{b}AMM@{ub} scans directories recursively, collects all files and inserts
     them into it's internal search tree.

@{i}options@{ui} and @{i}switches@{ui}
     These items always begin with one @{b}-@{ub} or two dashes @{b}-@{ub} and give you a
     finer control over @{b}AMM@{ub}'s behaviour.

The files collected by @{b}AMM@{ub} -- no matter whether they appear in a file
list or in the command line -- are always checked for existence, and
non-existent files or directories are simply ignored.  However, if the
@{b}-x@{ub} switched is given in the command line, @{b}AMM@{ub} will also process
non-existent files.  Here is a list of all options and switches:

@{b} @@{ub} @{i}filename@{ui}: Read a list of files
@{b}-@{ub} or @{b}-stdin@{ub}: Read a file list from stdin
     The @{b} @@{ub} option allows you to pass a list of files to @{b}AMM@{ub}.  This is
     important since on the one hand the length of a command line is
     limited on most systems and on the other hand @{b}AMM@{ub} does not know
     anything about patterns or regular expressions.  In general, a
     command like @{b}List@{ub} or @{b}ls@{ub} gives you much more power over the process
     of file gathering.  For example,
          List >ram:foobar FILES PAT ~(#?.info) LFORMAT "%p%n" DIR incoming:

     will non-recursively collect all files which are not icons from
     your @{b}incoming:@{ub} directory into a file @{b}ram:foobar@{ub}.

     A special version of the @{b} @@{ub} option is @{b}-@{ub} or @{b}-stdin@{ub}.  This forces
     @{b}AMM@{ub} to read the file list from the standard input stream which
     e.g. allows piping the file list to @{b}AMM@{ub} like that:
          List FILES LFORMAT "%p%n" | amm -f ADT_AMINET -y touch

     The number of file lists passed to @{b}AMM@{ub} is not limited but only
     depends on the available free store.  However you can pass the
     @{b}-stdin@{ub} option only once of course.

          @{i}Caution:@{ui} If @{b}-stdin@{ub} is used then the index file must be either
          specified via the @{b}-f@{ub} option or the environment variable
          @{b}ENV:ADTFILE@{ub} must be set to a valid index file.  @{b}AMM@{ub} will of
          course not be able to read the index file from the standard
          input stream as well in this case.

     Note also that the name `file list' might lead to the conclusion
     that only files can be part of @{b}AMM@{ub}'s file lists.  This is however
     not correct.  The file list must contain exactly one @{i}unquoted@{ui} path
     or filename per line; empty lines are ignored.  Directories are
     expanded recursively.

@{b}-y@{ub} or @{b}-yes-file@{ub} @{i}filename@{ui}: Script for indexed files
@{b}-n@{ub} or @{b}-no-file@{ub} @{i}filename@{ui}: Script for non-indexed files
     With these two options you can tell @{b}AMM@{ub} what to do.  At least one
     of them @{i}must@{ui} be present in the command line.

     If invoked with @{b}-y filename@{ub}, @{b}AMM@{ub} will read the file @{b}filename@{ub}, and
     for each file in the input which also exists in the index file,
     @{b}AMM@{ub} will expand the @{b}%@{ub}-macros in @{b}filename@{ub} and write the result
     to the standard output stream or the file specified with the @{b}-o@{ub}
     option, respectively.  The same applies to @{b}-n filename@{ub}, however
     this file will be expanded and written for those files which are
     @{i}not@{ui} listed in the index file.

          @{i}Note:@{ui} @{b}AMM@{ub} will automatically append a suffix @{b}.amm@{ub} to the
          given filename if the plain file @{b}filaname@{ub} does not exist.  If
          still unsuccessful, @{b}AMM@{ub} will look up the value of the
          environment variable @{b}ENV:AMMPATH@{ub} and search the directory it
          is set to for both @{b}filename@{ub} and @{b}filename.amm@{ub}.  For example,
               SetEnv AMMPATH s:amm/

          can be used to foce @{b}AMM@{ub} to look into the @{b}s:amm/@{ub} directory if
          the given script file does not exist in your current
          directory.  Use the following command to make it resident:
               Echo NOLINE "s:amm/" >ENVARC:AMMPATH

     The following @{b}%@{ub}-macros can be used in the script files:
    @{b}%n@{ub}
          The name of the file without a path.  This string will be
          taken from the index file if @{b}%n@{ub} appears in a file loaded with
          the @{b}-y@{ub} option to ensure correct capitalization.

    @{b}%p@{ub}
          The pathname of the input file, i.e. the location where the
          local file resides on your disk.  (e.g. @{b}incoming:@{ub}).  The
          replacement for @{b}%p@{ub} will @{i}always@{ui} have a trailing slash @{b}/@{ub} or
          colon @{b}:@{ub}.

    @{b}%d@{ub}
          The directory of the file in the Aminet including a trailing
          slash @{b}/@{ub}.  This is something like @{b}util/misc/@{ub} or @{b}biz/demo/@{ub}.
          This macro is of course not expanded in files loaded via @{b}-n@{ub}.

    @{b}%c@{ub}
          The comment of the file in the Aminet with all double quotes
          @{b}"@{ub} replaced with @{b}*"@{ub} and single asterisks @{b}*@{ub} replaced with
          @{b}**@{ub}.  This allows something like
               FileNote QUIET FILE "%p%n" COMMENT "%c"

          This macro is not expanded in files loaded via @{b}-n@{ub}.

    @{b}%D, %T@{ub}
          Respectively date and time of the upload.  These strings are
          valid for the @{b}SetDate@{ub} command and can be used for example
          like that:
               SetDate FILE "%p%n" DATE "%D" TIME "%T"

          These macros are not expanded in files loaded via @{b}-n@{ub}.

    @{b}%%@{ub}
          Always replaced with a single percent character @{b}%@{ub}.

     Other macros (such as @{b}%x@{ub} or @{b}%y@{ub}) actually expand to themselves.  It
     is however dangerous to rely on that because they might do not in
     future versions of @{b}AMM@{ub}.  If you really need something like @{b}%x@{ub} then
     you should better write @{b}%%x@{ub} instead.

@{b}-f@{ub}  or @{b}-index-file@{ub} @{i}filename@{ui}: Specify an ADT Aminet index file
     With this option you can specify the name of the Aminet index
     file.  If omitted, @{b}AMM@{ub} will read the index from the standard input
     stream unless and environment variable @{b}ADTINDEX@{ub} is set to a valid
     filename.  For example,
          set ADTINDEX=incoming:ADT_RECENT

     will force @{b}AMM@{ub} to read the index from @{b}incoming:ADT_RECENT@{ub} instead
     of from @{b}stdin@{ub}.  If this file is non-existent and @{b}-f@{ub} is omitted then
     @{b}AMM@{ub} will fail.  You can use the pseudo filename @{b}-@{ub} to force @{b}AMM@{ub} to
     read from @{b}stdin@{ub} even if @{b}ADTINDEX@{ub} is set.

@{b}-o@{ub}  or @{b}-output-file@{ub} @{i}filename@{ui}: Name of the output file
     @{b}AMM@{ub} will normally write all output to the standard output stream.
     With this option however you can force @{b}AMM@{ub} to write into the file
     @{i}filname@{ui} instead.  This can be useful if your environment does not
     support redirectioning of @{b}stdout@{ub}.  For example,
          amm -y touch incoming: -o ram:doit

     and
          amm -y touch incoming: >ram:doit
     are absolutely equivalent.

@{b}-h@{ub} or @{b}-help@{ub}: Print short usage information and exit
     When invoked with this option, @{b}AMM@{ub} displays a short usage
     information and exits.  You may also use @{b}-h1@{ub} to see only the
     "short" options (those with only one leading dash @{b}-@{ub}) or @{b}-h2@{ub} to see
     only the "long" options (those with two leading dashes @{b}-@{ub}).

@{b}-r@{ub} or @{b}-no-readmes@{ub}: Do not handle @{b}*.readme@{ub} files
     By default, @{b}AMM@{ub} will find the @{b}*.readme@{ub} files in the index even if
     they are not explicitly mentioned there (as it is the default in
     @{b}adt-v2@{ub} type index files).  However, when invoked with this option,
     @{b}AMM@{ub} will only find those files which really exist in the index
     file and ignore the @{b}.readme@{ub}s completely.

     Let me explain what @{b}AMM@{ub} does, if the @{b}-r@{ub} option is @{i}omitted@{ui}: The
     @{b}adt-v1@{ub} index file format also holds the names of the @{b}*.readme@{ub}
     files, so @{b}AMM@{ub} will use these to expand the @{b}%n@{ub} of a @{b}.readme@{ub} file if
     you feed such an index.  Otherwise, if the index file is of type
     @{b}adt-v2@{ub} then @{b}AMM@{ub} will cut off the original suffix and append
     @{b}.readme@{ub} instead.  All the @{b}%@{ub}-macros of the original file are
     copied to those of the @{b}.readme@{ub} file but only the @{b}%n@{ub} macro has the
     new suffix @{b}.readme@{ub}.

@{b}-v@{ub} or @{b}-verbose@{ub}: Print warnings and progress information
     This switch instructs @{b}AMM@{ub} to print some information to the
     standard error stream.  By default, @{b}AMM@{ub} will behave absolutely
     silent and only print error messages.  Note that @{b}-v@{ub} should be the
     first option!

@{b}-x@{ub}  or @{b}-ignore-exist@{ub}: Lookup also non-existent files
     By default, @{b}AMM@{ub} will only insert existent files into it's search
     tree.  Non-existent files passed to @{b}AMM@{ub} are simply ignored.  With
     this option you can force @{b}AMM@{ub} to process also those files which do
     not really exist on your disk.  This can be useful when working
     with file lists.
          @{i}Caution:@{ui} If a non-existent pathname with a trailing slash @{b}/@{ub}
          or colon @{b}:@{ub} is passed to @{b}AMM@{ub} and the @{b}-x@{ub} switch is present,
          then @{b}AMM@{ub} will insert an empty file @{b}""@{ub} with the given
          pathname.  In this case the result of a search in the index
          file is unpredictable!

     Note also that since @{b}AMM@{ub} traverses the command line from left to
     right, the @{b}-x@{ub} switch has infuence on only those files or pathnames
     which are mentioned @{i}right@{ui} of it.  In general it is a good idea to
     use @{b}-x@{ub} as the very first switch, if needed.


@EndNode

@Node "Configuring AMM" "MirrorManager.guide/Configuring AMM"
@Next "Hints & Tips"
@Prev "Options & Switches"
@Toc "AMM"

Configuring AMM For Your Mirror
-------------------------------

As explained in the description of the options @{b}-y@{ub} and @{b}-n@{ub}, @{b}AMM@{ub} expands
macros for indexed and/or non-indexed files respectively.  See
@{"Options & Switches" Link "Options & Switches"}, for more information.  We shall now explain some
example scripts to help you getting some experience in writing such
scripts for your system.

One of the most important script is @{b}touch.amm@{ub}.  It sets the file date
and comment according to the values in the index file.  This is very
useful, especially if you're using a tool like @{b}DOpus@{ub} to examine the
downloaded files.  With @{b}touch.amm@{ub} you can get the filenote in the @{b}DOpus@{ub}
listview as you are used to when downloading via @{b}adt@{ub}.
     ; $VER: $ld: touch.amm,v 1.3 1995/07/26 03:08:45 tf Exp $
     ; (c)Copyright 1995 by Tobias Ferber,  All Rights Reserved
     
     If EXISTS "%p%n"
       Echo "%d%n (%c)"
       SetDate FILE "%p%n" DATE "%D" TIME "%T"
       FileNote QUIET FILE "%p%n" COMMENT "%c"
     EndIf

We need the @{b}If EXISTS@{ub} ... @{b}EndIf@{ub} to avoid errors because -- especially
when invoked with the @{b}-x@{ub} switch -- @{b}AMM@{ub} will also process files which
don't really exist on your disk.

Another very useful script is @{b}cleanup.amm@{ub} which is quite similar to
@{b}touch.amm@{ub}, but additionally moves the files to your local Aminet
mirror.  The following example assumes your mirror in @{b}downloads:aminet/@{ub}.

     ; $VER: $ld: cleanup.amm 1.4 1995/07/26 03:08:41 tf Exp $
     ; (c)Copyright 1995 by Tobias Ferber,  All Rights Reserved
     
     If EXISTS "%p%n"
       SetDate FILE "%p%n" DATE "%D" TIME "%T"
       FileNote QUIET FILE "%p%n" COMMENT "%c"
       Copy QUIET CLONE FROM "%p%n" TO "downloads:aminet/%d%n"
       Delete QUIET FILE "%p%n"
     EndIf

@{i}Warning:@{ui} The @{b}Delete@{ub} is of course dangerous and might kill your original
file if you run @{b}amm -y cleanup@{ub} directly on your mirror directory
@{b}downloads:aminet/@{ub}!

One possible enhancement would be using Kai Iske's @{b}Move@{ub} command instead
of @{b}Copy@{ub} and @{b}Delete@{ub}.  For example,
     Move QUIET CLONE FROM "%p%n" TO "downloads:aminet/%d%n"


@EndNode

@Node "Hints & Tips" "MirrorManager.guide/Hints & Tips"
@Prev "Configuring AMM"
@Toc "AMM"

Hints & Tips For Efficient AMM Utilization
------------------------------------------

This section is supposed to give you some deeper insight into @{b}AMM@{ub}'s
work and to show you some special solutions for problems which you
wouldn't have if you wouldn't use @{b}AMM@{ub}. @{b}:)@{ub}

Catching the index file from MUIAdt
...................................

I most often use @{b}MUIAdt@{ub} to download files from the Aminet.  @{b}MUIAdt@{ub}
automatically downloads the @{b}info/adt/RECENT.adt.Z@{ub} or
@{b}info/adt/SHORT.adt.Z@{ub} file respectively, however it deletes it
immediately when exiting so you most likely forget copying the file to
a safe location.  One way to solve this problem is via @{b}WaitNotify@{ub}; for
example,
     Copy `WaitNotify FMT=%s RAM:RECENT.adt RAM:SHORT.adt` incoming:

This will save a copy of the first index file which appears in your @{b}Ram
Disk:@{ub} into your @{b}incoming:@{ub} directory.  It's a good idea to put the
following lines into your @{b}AmiTCP/bin/startnet@{ub} script:
     Echo >T:grab-adt "Copy *`WaitNotify FMT=%s RAM:RECENT.adt*` incoming:"
     Run <NIL: >NIL: Execute T:grab-adt

Removing From Your Mirror What Is Available On CD
.................................................

Many of you who use @{b}AMM@{ub} might also have the @{b}Aminet5:@{ub} CD.  Now why
should you keep all those files on your harddisk if you've got them on
a CD?  So I thought and home I went writing the following script which
(re)moves the those files from my @{b}downloads:aminet/@{ub} drawer.  Actually
I'm not that keen on using the @{b}Delete@{ub} command immediately, and so I
decided to make a new drawer @{b}downloads:aminet5/@{ub} and move the mentioned
files out of my mirror into it using the following @{b}cd5.amm@{ub} script:
     If EXISTS "%p%n"
       Echo "%d%n (%c)"
       Move QUIET CLONE FROM "%p%n" TO "downloads:aminet5/%n"
     EndIf

Again I used Kai Iske's excellent @{b}Move@{ub} command instead of @{b}Copy@{ub} and
@{b}Delete@{ub}.  To execute this script you simply have to type the following:
     amm -y cd5 downloads:aminet/ -f AMINET5:Aminet/info/adt/ADT_AMINET |ex

The @{b}ex@{ub} command is explained in one of the following sections.  See @{"Ex" Link "Ex"},
for details.


@EndNode

@Node "ALs" "MirrorManager.guide/ALs"
@Next "Ex"
@Prev "AMM"
@Toc "Additional Tools"

ALs - Create Aminet Index Files
===============================

The @{b}ALs@{ub} command creates index files in various formats from your local
mirror directory.  To be more precise: @{b}ALs@{ub} collects all files in a
given path (or in the current directory, if omitted) and writes those
which are nested @{i}two@{ui} subdirectories deep in form of an index file to
the standard output stream.(1)

@{b}ALs@{ub} will preferably take the desctiption text from the @{b}.readme@{ub} file's
@{b}Short:@{ub} line however, if there's no @{b}.readme@{ub} file available it will use
the filenote instead.

Installation
------------

Installing @{b}ALs@{ub} is very easy: Simply copy @{b}als.000@{ub} (or @{b}als.030@{ub} if you
have an MC-68030 Amiga) somewhere into your path (e.g. to @{b}C:@{ub}) and
rename it to @{b}als@{ub}.  For example,
     Copy CLONE als.000 TO c:als

Invoking ALs
------------

By default, @{b}ALs@{ub} creates has an 80 columns wide @{b}SHORT@{ub} index file as
output and reads from the current directory.  You can however control
@{b}ALs@{ub} via the following options.  (Note that options must be specified
@{i}before@{ui} the path name)

@{b}-f1@{ub}, @{b}-f2@{ub}: Create machine readable @{b}ADT@{ub} index files
     With these options, @{b}ALs@{ub} writes index files of type @{b}adt-v1@{ub} or
     @{b}adt-v2@{ub}, respectively.  Actually, the name of the @{b}*.readme@{ub}
     files in the @{b}adt-v1@{ub} index is created for all files by changing the
     original suffix to @{b}.readme@{ub}.  The size of them is @{i}always@{ui} set to @{b}0@{ub},
     because actually all @{b}*.readme@{ub} files are simply ignored.  This
     might change in future versions.

@{b}-fs@{ub}, @{b}-fl@{ub}: Create human readable index files
     These options set @{b}ALs@{ub}'s output format to those known from the
     @{b}SHORT@{ub} and @{b}LONG@{ub} index files, respectively.  By default, @{b}ALs@{ub}
     uses @{b}-fs@{ub}. The main difference is that the file comment in the
     @{b}SHORT@{ub} index file is truncated to 42 characters, whereas it is
     up to 80 characters wide in the @{b}LONG@{ub} index file, which
     additionally provides an @{b}Age@{ub} column with the age of each file in
     days.  However, 20 characters are reserved for the filename in
     @{b}SHORT@{ub} index files, whereas there are only 18 characters reserved
     for the filename in the @{b}LONG@{ub} index file format.

@{b}-ft@{ub}: Create an Aminet tree file
     With this option, @{b}ALs@{ub} prints a tree file for the given directory.
     The desctiption text will be preferably taken from the first line
     of a file @{b}.message@{ub} however if it doesn't exist, @{b}ALs@{ub} will use the
     directory's filenote.

@{b}-fg@{ub}, @{b}-fh@{ub}: Create AmigaGuide/HTML index files (experimental!)
     These Options are still under development.  They work, but the
     result is not very nice yet.

@{b}-d@{ub} @{i}directory@{ui}: Make given path a certain directory
     By default, @{b}ALs@{ub} only prints files which are nested two directories
     deeper than the given path.  With this option you can tell @{b}ALs@{ub}
     that when scanning the given path, it has already entered the
     given @{i}directory@{ui}.  For example:
          als -d util downloads:aminet/util

     will print the index for the @{b}util/@{ub} directory only.  Of course you
     can also print the contents of your @{b}incoming:@{ub} directory via @{b}als -d
     foo/bar incoming:@{ub}.

@{b}-@{ub} @{i}dayrange@{ui}
     This option allows you to restrict the files included into the
     output to be at most @{i}dayrange@{ui} days old.  For example
          als -14 >RECENT

     creates a file @{b}RECENT@{ub} which contains all files of the last two
     weeks.

@{i}Example:@{ui} Suppose you have an Aminet mirror in your @{b}downloads:aminet/@{ub}
directory and now you want to create a file @{b}RECENT.adt.Z@{ub} to allow other
people to connect to your Amiga via @{b}MUIAdt@{ub}.  Here is what you have to
type:
     als -f1 -14 downloads:aminet | compress >downloads:aminet/info/adt/RECENT.adt.Z

---------- Footnotes ----------

(1)  Note that @{b}ALs@{ub} additionally hides both: files and directories
beginning with a period @{b}.@{ub} and @{b}*.readme@{ub} files


@EndNode

@Node "Ex" "MirrorManager.guide/Ex"
@Prev "ALs"
@Toc "Additional Tools"

Ex - Execute Shell Scripts From A Pipe
======================================

The @{b}Ex@{ub} command is an enhancement of @{b}C:Execute@{ub}.  The advantages of @{b}Ex@{ub}
over @{b}C:Execute@{ub} are:
   -     @{b}Ex@{ub} allows @{i}multiple@{ui} file names of shell scripts to execute in
     the command line instead of only one

   -     @{b}Ex@{ub} has a @{b}QUIET/S@{ub} switch to suppress console output of @{i}any@{ui} of
     the commands in the given script files.

   -     @{b}Ex@{ub} can execute a shell script from the pipe (!)

   -     @{b}Ex@{ub} can execute shell scripts asynchronously (i.e. @{b}Run@{ub} them).

Installation
------------

Installing @{b}Ex@{ub} is very easy: Simply copy @{b}ex.000@{ub} (or @{b}ex.030@{ub} if you have an
MC-68030 Amiga) somewhere into your path (e.g. to @{b}C:@{ub}) and rename it to
@{b}ex@{ub}.  For example,
     Copy CLONE ex.000 TO c:ex

That's all! @{b}:)@{ub}


@EndNode

